gpu9 — Intel Gen8 (Broadwell) GPU driver for 9front, entirely in userspace.

0.1.0  2026-07-15  first release

	What it does: gives 9front HARDWARE 2D ACCELERATION, which it has never
	had. 9front runs `hwaccel off` / `softscreen on` — the CPU pushes every
	pixel by hand through an uncached aperture. gpu9 hands fills and scrolls
	to the GPU's blitter instead.

	The headline, verified on bare metal (readback-checked):
	    gpu9 fill    GPU 9892 MB/s vs CPU 15 MB/s = 646x   (clear 1024x768)
	    gpu9 scroll  GPU 4426 MB/s vs CPU 13 MB/s = 328x   (scroll up 16px)
	The CPU reaches framebuffer memory only through the aperture (13-15
	MB/s); the blitter is native to it. `gpu9 demo` draws on the live screen
	so you can see it. gpu9_fill() / gpu9_blt() are library primitives, not
	just commands — the seam a terminal or draw device would hook.

	Why it is fast: gpu9 also manages the CLOCK, which nothing else on
	9front does. With no driver, Broadwell parks at 100 MHz of 800 forever;
	one register write (RPS) makes it 6.7x faster. `gpu9 rps` proves it.

	Honest about the wrong workload: for plain RAM-to-RAM copies the GPU is
	NOT a win — the CPU cache beats it below 4MB, ties at 4MB. `gpu9 bench`
	shows this and verifies every copy. A GPU does not copy your cached RAM;
	it operates on the framebuffer, where the 300-650x above is real.
	cirno's GT1 (12 EUs) is the weakest Broadwell made — the win is not raw
	power, it is that the CPU has no fast path to VRAM and the GPU does.

	Also verified: MMIO, forcewake, GTT/aperture memory, the legacy ring,
	batch buffers with correct fences. `gpu9 test` self-checks.

	NOT included: 3D/OpenGL. Mesa's iris compiles and links for 9front
	(1027/1027 TUs via cc9) but is not wired to gpu9 — iris is softpin-only
	and wants a 0..12GB address space where gpu9 has a 64MB GGTT. For
	software OpenGL today, use gl9.

	SECURITY — read before installing. A process holding GPU MMIO + the GTT
	can program the engine to DMA anywhere in physical memory, kernel
	included. That is full privilege escalation for anyone who can open
	those segments, and it is a real reason Linux keeps DRM in the kernel.
	This is opt-in on purpose and should never be a default. Fine on a box
	you own; do not install it on a machine you share.

	Requires: `echo type igfx >/dev/vgactl` once per boot, so the kernel
	registers the igfxmmio/igfxscreen segments. That only maps and
	registers them — it does not program your display.
